<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Guardians Ass'n
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 v. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Civil Service Commission of the City of New York,
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 463 U.S. 582 (1983); 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Regents of the University of California
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 v. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Bakke,
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 438 U.S. 265 (1978). Thus, the Department's interpretation of the general language of the Title VI regulations concerning
permissible affirmative action is based on case law under both Title VI and the Fourteenth Amendment. 
